{"disposition":"accepted","experiment_id":"WM-001","findings":[{"id":"F001","resolution":"resolved","severity":"major","summary":"The v1.8 matrix-contract identity serialized two set-derived arrays without ordering, so fresh interpreter hash randomization could change an otherwise accepted closure digest."},{"id":"F002","resolution":"resolved","severity":"major","summary":"The initial v1.9 fresh-reopen validator compared producer and result digests with nonexistent top-level closure fields and would have rejected every real closure late in the one-shot path."},{"id":"F003","resolution":"resolved","severity":"major","summary":"The initial accepted-closure preformal stdout check only type-checked producer and result digests, allowing rewritten semantic identities if logs and report references were also rewritten."},{"id":"F004","resolution":"resolved","severity":"major","summary":"The first real nested inherited-descriptor child would otherwise have run only after the development outcome existed, leaving lock non-recursion and descriptor exec unproven before the one-shot producer."},{"id":"F005","resolution":"resolved","severity":"major","summary":"The closure documentation initially conflated the required unretained prepublication fresh reopen with the distinct retained post-marker, pre-attempt-finalization fresh reopen receipt."},{"id":"F006","resolution":"informational","severity":"note","summary":"Fresh identity and closure children enter the inherited captured bootstrap and runtime-seal descriptors directly, bypassing the launcher and therefore never recursively acquiring the held outer lock."},{"id":"F007","resolution":"informational","severity":"note","summary":"The v1.9 schemas, canonical paths, fresh seeds, 10/1360 current and 80/10880 prior seed universes, zero cross-domain collisions, and matrix golden were independently reproduced."},{"id":"F008","resolution":"informational","severity":"note","summary":"The 17-block scientific digest and all four scientifi